Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and hook into Shell's `Navigating` event:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating += OnShellNavigating;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating -= OnShellNavigating;
    }

    // Intercepts Shell navigation (including toolbar back button)
    private async void OnShellNavigating(object sender, ShellNavigatingEventArgs e)
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return;

        var deferral = e.GetDeferral();

        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and leave?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave)
            e.Cancel();      // cancel navigation

        deferral.Complete();
    }

    // Intercepts Android/device hardware back button
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and leave?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
            {
                _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            }
        });

        return true; // true = we handled it, suppress default
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, hide the default back button and add a toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>
</ContentPage>
```

Or set it inline:

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        IsVisible="True"
                        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

With the command in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand => new Command(async () =>
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard and leave?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave) return;
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
});
```

**Key points:**

- **`Shell.Navigating` + `GetDeferral()`** — lets you asynchronously confirm, then cancel or proceed. This catches the software back button.
- **`OnBackButtonPressed()`** — catches the Android hardware/gesture back; return `true` to suppress default behavior.
- **`BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride`** — replaces the back arrow with "Cancel" text. Setting `Command` overrides the default navigation so your confirmation logic runs.
